Îâ¥Ïä§Ï†úÎ™©: Helium, Building Out Mobile Network, Plans to Give Free Trials to Solana Phone Users
Î≥∏Î¨∏: Nova Labs, the company behind Helium Network and a new crypto-powered cellular service called Helium Mobile, said it would provide SIM cards and free trials to customers of Solana Labs‚Äô new Saga phones.  The companies declined to disclose financial details on the plan, which comes after Helium Network community members voted in September to ditch its own blockchain and migrate over to the larger Solana blockchain.  Under the agreement, Saga phones sold in the U.S. will get a 30-day free subscription to Helium Mobile, according to a press release. Saga phones are Solana‚Äôs flagship Android device, tightly integrated with the Solana blockchain.  The Helium Network is a decentralized grid of wireless hotspots that aims to provide an alternative to hard-wired internet or mobile data service. The services are powered by cryptocurrencies; people who participate in the network receive rewards for doing so.  Helium is incentivizing development of the 5G network by offering MOBILE tokens to users who deploy the 5G hotspots. This is similar to the company‚Äôs IoT crypto mining model, where users would earn HNT tokens for running hotspots.  Nova Labs has faced challenges trying to simultaneously build out two networks for ‚Äúinternet of things‚Äù connectivity and for mobile coverage. Helium Mobile, the cellular-focused service, isn‚Äôt expected to launch until the first quarter of 2023, and the company recently inked a five-year agreement with cellular giant T-Mobile to cover the anticipated dead spots.  ‚ÄúAs we gear up to launch the world‚Äôs first cryptocarrier, our partnership will help bring low-cost, reliable and decentralized 5G coverage to Saga users across the U.S,‚Äù said Boris Renski, general manager of wireless for Nova Labs.

Î≥∏Î¨∏: Web3 messaging startup Dialect is rolling out tech specs to help crypto projects communicate between themselves, an effort the Solana-focused company hopes will morph into a standard for the industry.  Dialect is calling it a ‚Äúsmart messaging specification‚Äù that‚Äôs already captured the interest of 50 fellow startups, CEO Chris Osborn told CoinDesk. Starting Saturday, they (and anyone, really) can check out Dialect‚Äôs open-source codebase to begin building integrations themselves.  The tech is built on the foundations of Solana Labs‚Äô payment infrastructure, though it doesn‚Äôt move tokens or value about. Instead, it moves actionable notifications. Little email-like pop-ups with a ‚Äúcall to action‚Äù hook that let the recipient do the thing ‚Äì whatever that thing is ‚Äì right then and there.  In an interview at the Solana Breakpoint conference in Lisbon, Osborn gave the example of a musician orchestrating a non-fungible token (NFT) mint via her own distribution platform. Let‚Äôs say (under the current tech landscape) her fans receive an email blast alerting them the mint window has opened. But: they have to click through to a different link, hook in their wallet, press the button ‚Äì do the thing. With Dialect‚Äôs smart messaging standard she could set up the initial notification to include the mechanism for them to simply execute the mint.  ‚ÄúWe carry our wallet between every dapp, NFT, [decentralized finance] protocol ‚Äì everything we do in crypto, we‚Äôre authenticating in the same way,‚Äù Osborn said.

Îâ¥Ïä§Ï†úÎ™©: Litecoin Mining Difficulty Is Hitting New Highs, Foundation Says
Î≥∏Î¨∏: Litecoin mining difficulty is at a new high, peaking at just under 18 million hashes, according to a post by the Litecoin Foundation on cryptocurrency market data site coinmarketcap.com.  Mining difficulty measures the average number of hashes required to ‚Äúsolve‚Äù a block. Litecoin miners compete by generating random hashes to find one lower than the target set by the network‚Äôs mining algorithm. Whoever wins this computationally intensive lottery gets to add a new block to the Litecoin blockchain and earns a reward.  The increase in Litecoin‚Äôs mining difficulty likely means the competition for miner rewards is heating up.  The cryptocurrency, sometimes referred to as ‚Äúdigital silver,‚Äù also has a ‚Äúhalvening‚Äù event on the horizon. When Litecoin was launched in 2011, miners received 50 litecoins (LTC) for successfully mining a block. That reward (called a ‚Äúsubsidy‚Äù) is halved every 840,000 blocks (roughly every four years). The third halving takes place in 2023 and reduces the current 12.5 LTC subsidy to 6.25 LTC.  The price of LTC is holding steady, trading at $68.04 at the time of publication. However, on Wednesday, LTC‚Äôs price spiked 13% in a single day, probably due to payments giant MoneyGram‚Äôs announcement that its U.S. customers will soon be able to buy, sell and hold LTC, bitcoin (BTC) and ether (ETH) in the MoneyGram mobile app.  Read more: MoneyGram Debuts Crypto Purchases on Mobile App
